## Principle 1: Understand what your source is actually giving you before you build anything

*What should someone know before they attempt to represent cultural material as data?*

**Daria:**
- Different sources covering the same cultural phenomenon return data at completely different levels of detail — one might give you a full text, another a two-sentence summary, another a four-word title. These are not interchangeable, and which one you use determines which methods can actually work on it.
- The same item can appear across multiple databases in slightly different forms. Deduplication is not optional — without it you are counting the same thing twice and your totals mean nothing.
- A curated database already reflects someone else's interpretive decisions about what belongs in it. The moment you use a pre-built source, you inherit those decisions whether you know it or not.
- Some collections include items at different stages — drafts, proposals, finished works, rejected versions. You have to decide explicitly which ones to include and document that decision, because it will shape your findings either way.

**Adin:**
- Sometimes, the time you spend thinking about and planning what you have to do is just as important as what you actually do. Keep records that you can reference later, because you never know when they'll be helpful.
- There will always be more you think you can add to try and make things more accurate or better somehow, at some point, you have to call things good enough so you can move to more important matters.

**Christina:**

**Vedha:**
- Working with museum APIs showed me that “available data” is already a filtered version of cultural history. Even when scraping at scale, what is returned is shaped by institutional tagging systems, search rankings, and what has been digitized in the first place. This means the dataset is not discovering culture, but reproducing what institutions have made searchable.
- I learned that even simple fields like title, medium, or date are not neutral. They depend on cataloging standards that vary across museums, which makes normalization a required but interpretively loaded step.
- A major hidden decision is query design. The keywords used to pull data effectively determine what cultural objects appear in the dataset before any analysis even begins.

